## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised — dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points. The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken for timely cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }

    // Async overload — preferred in modern .NET code.
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Example

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// The work lambda now receives a CancellationToken it must respect.
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();   // cooperative check
        // ... do a chunk of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Non-cooperative work won't stop** | Unlike `Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative* — if the delegate ignores the token, it runs to completion. There is no safe way to forcibly kill work in .NET 8. |
| **Signature change is breaking** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>` — all callers must be updated. Provide a **shim** (below) if you need a gradual rollout. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** | The original code created a dedicated thread. For long-running CPU work, pass `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to `Task.Factory.StartNew` instead. |
| **`AggregateException` wrapping** | The original manually wrapped exceptions. `Task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` already unwraps to the inner exception — don't double-wrap. |
| **`WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | Safe on .NET 8, but won't compile on older targets. |

### Backward-Compatible Shim (for gradual migration)

```csharp
// Lets old Func<T> callers compile, but they lose cancellation support.
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => work(), timeout);
}
```

> **Bottom line:** Replace every `Thread.Abort` with cooperative `CancellationToken` checks. There is no drop-in equivalent — this is an intentional design change in modern .NET.
